First, we introduce variables \(u = \log x\), \(v = \log y\), and \(w = \log z\). Substituting these into the equations, we get: 1. \(uv - u - 3v - 3\log 5 - 3\log 2 = -4\) 2. \(vw - 4v - w - 4\log 2 - 4\log 5 = 4\) 3. \(uw - 4u - 3w - 12\log 2 - 12\log 5 = -18\) Using the fact that \(\log 2 + \log 5 = 1\), we simplify the equations: 1. \((u - 3)(v - 1) = 2\) 2. \((v - 1)(w - 4) = 12\) 3. \((u - 3)(w - 4) = 6\) Introducing new variables \(a = u - 3\), \(b = v - 1\), and \(c = w - 4\), we get: 1. \(ab = 2\) 2. \(bc = 12\) 3. \(ac = 6\) Solving these, we find \(a = 1\), \(b = 2\), \(c = 6\) or \(a = -1\), \(b = -2\), \(c = -6\). Converting back to \(u, v, w\): - Case 1: \(u = 4\), \(v = 3\), \(w = 10\) - Case 2: \(u = 2\), \(v = -1\), \(w = -2\) Checking both cases in the original equations, we find that only Case 2 satisfies all equations with \(a = -4\), \(b = 4\), and \(c = -18\). Thus, \(u = 2\), \(v = -1\), \(w = -2\) translates back to: \[ \begin{aligned} \log x = 2 & \implies x = 10^2 = 100, \\ \log y = -1 & \implies y = 10^{-1} = 0.1, \\ \log z = -2 & \implies z = 10^{-2} = 0.01. \end{aligned} \] The solutions are: \[ \boxed{x = 100}, \quad \boxed{y = \dfrac{1}{10}}, \quad \boxed{z = \dfrac{1}{100}} \]
